Derivative $f(x,y)$ is a surface in $\mathbb{R}- 3$ it is the slope of surface at a point -&gt; $\infty$ number of lines Find the slope of the tangent line to a surface at a point. we must give the tangent line a Direction For now, we restrict our direction to in the &lsquo;X-Direction(Axis)&rsquo; or in the &lsquo;y-Direction&rsquo; To find the slope of tangent line in &lsquo;X-Direction&rsquo;, we must contain the tangent line in a plane parallel to teh xz-Plane Requires &ldquo;y&rdquo; to be constant Notation $$ egin{align} f(x,y) =&amp; z 
ewline  rac{\partial f}{\partial x},  rac{\partial z}{\partial x}, f_{x}, z_{x}:\ &amp;	ext{Holds &lsquo;y&rsquo; constant} 
ewline &amp;	ext{Slope of tangent line ot the surface at a point in x-direction} 
ewline  rac{\partial f}{\partial y},  rac{\partial z}{\partial y}, f_{y}, z_{y}:\ &amp;	ext{Holds &lsquo;x&rsquo; constant} 
ewline &amp;	ext{Slope of tangent line of the surface at apoint in y-direction} \end{align}$$

Velocity and Acceleration $$ egin{align} 	ext{Given vector funciton }&amp;\vec{r}(t) 
ewline 	ext{Velocity: }&amp;\vec{v}(t) = \vec{r}\prime(t) 
ewline 	ext{Acceleration: }&amp;\vec{a}(t) = \vec{v}\prime(t) = \vec{r}\prime\prime(t) 
ewline 	ext{Speed: }&amp;||\vec{v}(t)|| \end{align}$$ Example 1 Find Velocity, Accel and speed of a particle described by $\vec{r}(t) = \left&lt; t, t^2, t^3 ight&gt;$ at t = 1 $$ egin{align} 	ext{Velocity: } &amp;\vec{r}\prime(t) = \left&lt; 1, 2t, 3t^2 ight&gt; ightarrow \vec{v}(1) = \left&lt; 1, 2, 3 ight&gt; 
ewline 	ext{Speed: } &amp;||\vec{v}(1)|| = \sqrt{1+4+9} = \sqrt{14} 
